/roadtostudy.com/#website","url":"https://roadtostudy.com","name":"Road to Study - Turkey University Guide for Students","alternateName":"Road to Study in Turkey","publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/a-guide-to-turkeys-unesco-world-heritage-sites/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/a-guide-to-turkeys-unesco-world-heritage-sites/","name":"A Guide to Turkey’s UNESCO World Heritage Sites - RoadtoStudy","datePublished":"2026-04-18T14:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-04-18T14:00:00+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"A Guide to Turkey’s UNESCO World Heritage Sites - RoadtoStudy","datePublished":"2026-04-18T14:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-04-18T14:00:00+03:00","articleSection":"Student Life and Travel","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Discover Turkey&#039;s incredible UNESCO World Heritage sites. Start planning your trip today to explore these locations, which are rich in history and culture!","name":"A Guide to Turkey’s UNESCO World Heritage Sites - RoadtoStudy","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/a-guide-to-turkeys-unesco-world-heritage-sites/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/a-guide-to-turkeys-unesco-world-heritage-sites/#webpage"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/a-guide-to-turkeys-unesco-world-heritage-sites/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In addition to being a country rich in history and culture, Turkey also stands out for its remarkable UNESCO World Heritage Sites. In this article, we will provide comprehensive information about these sites, highlight why they are important for international students, and discuss how visiting them can be an enriching cultural experience.</p>
<h2 id="turkiyede-unesco-dunya-mirasi-alanlari-bir-kesif-rehberi" class="wp-block-heading">UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Turkey: A Discovery Guide</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey has a rich cultural heritage with 18 UNESCO World Heritage Sites. These sites offer visitors unique experiences with both their historical and natural beauty. Here are some of the key UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Turkey:</p>
<div id="model-response-message-contentr_7dc0e9532bb0e1b5" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">
<h3>Turkey’s UNESCO World Heritage Sites</h3>
<p>Turkey&#8217;s entries on the UNESCO World Heritage List are categorized under two main headings: cultural and mixed (natural and cultural) heritage.</p>
<h3>1. Mixed Heritage Sites</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<td>Site</td>
<td>Province</td>
<td>Inscription Year</td>
<td>Key Feature</td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Göreme National Park and the Rock Sites of Cappadocia</b></td>
<td>Nevşehir</td>
<td>1985</td>
<td>A unique natural landscape with fairy chimneys, cave churches, and underground settlements, featuring Christian architecture from the Byzantine period.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Hierapolis-Pamukkale</b></td>
<td>Denizli</td>
<td>1988</td>
<td>The natural beauty of travertine terraces combined with the ruins of the Roman-era thermal city of Hierapolis.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>2. Cultural Heritage Sites</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<td>Site</td>
<td>Province</td>
<td>Inscription Year</td>
<td>Key Feature</td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Historic Areas of Istanbul</b></td>
<td>İstanbul</td>
<td>1985</td>
<td>The multi-layered urban structure, as the capital of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empires, encompassing Hagia Sophia, Topkapı Palace, the Blue Mosque, and the Historic City Walls.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Great Mosque and Hospital of Divriği</b></td>
<td>Sivas</td>
<td>1985</td>
<td>A masterpiece of Anatolian Seljuk architecture; famous for its ornate portals, especially the one known as the &#8220;Gate of Heaven.&#8221;</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Hattusha: the Hittite Capital</b></td>
<td>Çorum</td>
<td>1986</td>
<td>The capital of the Hittite Empire. Features the Lion Gate, the Sphinx Gate, great temples, and archives of cuneiform tablets.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Nemrut Dağ</b></td>
<td>Adıyaman</td>
<td>1987</td>
<td>The summit featuring the tomb-sanctuary of King Antiochus I of Commagene and its colossal statues.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Xanthos-Letoon</b></td>
<td>Antalya – Muğla</td>
<td>1988</td>
<td>The ruins of the largest religious center (Letoon) and the largest city (Xanthos) of the Lycian civilization.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>City of Safranbolu</b></td>
<td>Karabük</td>
<td>1994</td>
<td>One of the best-preserved Ottoman urban settlements, featuring traditional wooden house architecture.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Archaeological Site of Troy</b></td>
<td>Çanakkale</td>
<td>1998</td>
<td>The ancient city with over 4,000 years of history, which was the setting for the epic poem, the Iliad.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Selimiye Mosque and its Social Complex</b></td>
<td>Edirne</td>
<td>2011</td>
<td>Known as Mimar Sinan&#8217;s &#8220;masterpiece,&#8221; representing the pinnacle of Ottoman architecture.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Neolithic Site of Çatalhöyük</b></td>
<td>Konya</td>
<td>2012</td>
<td>One of the world&#8217;s oldest and largest Neolithic settlements, dating back approximately 9,000 years.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Bursa and Cumalıkızık: the Birth of the Ottoman Empire</b></td>
<td>Bursa</td>
<td>2014</td>
<td>The first capital of the Ottoman Empire and a historic village (Cumalıkızık) representing the Ottoman urban/rural system.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Pergamon and its Multi-Layered Cultural Landscape</b></td>
<td>İzmir</td>
<td>2014</td>
<td>The Acropolis of Pergamon, a major center of the Hellenistic period, and the surrounding multi-layered cultural ruins.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Diyarbakır Fortress and Hevsel Gardens Cultural Landscape</b></td>
<td>Diyarbakır</td>
<td>2015</td>
<td>The cultural landscape formed by the 7,000-year-old Diyarbakır City Walls and the Hevsel Gardens on the banks of the Tigris River.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Ephesus</b></td>
<td>İzmir</td>
<td>2015</td>
<td>An important port city of the Hellenistic and Roman periods, which also housed the Temple of Artemis, one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Archaeological Site of Ani</b></td>
<td>Kars</td>
<td>2016</td>
<td>The ruins of the city known as the &#8220;City of 1001 Churches,&#8221; which was the capital of the medieval Bagratid Armenian Kingdom.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Aphrodisias</b></td>
<td>Aydın</td>
<td>2017</td>
<td>A center for the art of sculpture and the temple dedicated to the ancient Greek goddess Aphrodite.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Göbekli Tepe</b></td>
