<h2 id="turkiyede-yilbasi-kutlamalarinin-gelenekleri-ve-onemli-noktalari" class="wp-block-heading">Traditions and Highlights of New Year&#8217;s Celebrations in Turkey</h2>
<div id="model-response-message-contentr_fa442e969d94ed21" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">
<p>New Year&#8217;s celebrations in Turkey largely revolve around gathering with family and close friends, preparing lavish dinner tables, and participating in games of chance.</p>
<h3>1. The Excitement of the National Lottery and Games of Chance</h3>
<p>This is one of Turkey’s oldest and most widespread modern New Year&#8217;s traditions.</p>
<ul>
<li><b>The Milli Piyango New Year&#8217;s Special Draw:</b> The most thrilling moment of New Year&#8217;s Eve is the grand prize drawing of the state lottery. Millions of people try their luck by buying a quarter, half, or full ticket in the final days of the year and follow the draw on television or radio with great excitement.</li>
<li><b>Tombala (Bingo):</b> This is an essential New Year&#8217;s game played within families or among groups of friends. With its simple rules and ability to bring everyone from young to old together, it&#8217;s one of the night&#8217;s most entertaining activities.</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. Preparing Lavish Family Feasts</h3>
<p>New Year&#8217;s Eve means a feast night where people come together to enjoy meticulously prepared meals.</p>
<ul>
<li><b>New Year&#8217;s Turkey:</b> This has become the main course of New Year&#8217;s tables in Turkey. It is usually stuffed with &#8220;iç pilav&#8221; (a seasoned rice pilaf) and roasted to a golden brown, taking center stage on the table. This tradition became popular through interaction with Western culture.</li>
<li><b>Nuts and Fruits:</b> These are indispensable parts of the feast. Traditional nuts like <b>walnuts, hazelnuts, pistachios, and roasted chickpeas</b>, along with fruits like <b>pomegranate, dried figs, and dates</b>, are consumed in abundance.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. Rituals for Luck and Abundance</h3>
<p>Some popular customs performed with the wish that the new year brings prosperity and luck:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Smashing a Pomegranate:</b> Smashing a pomegranate in front of the house&#8217;s doorstep as the new year begins is a popular tradition for good luck. It is believed that the scattered seeds of the broken pomegranate will bring <b>abundance, prosperity, and luck</b> to the home.</li>
<li><b>Red Underwear:</b> This is common, especially among young people. The belief that wearing red underwear while welcoming the new year will bring <b>love and luck</b> in the coming year is a modernizing tradition.</li>
<li><b>Turning on the Taps:</b> In some places, symbolic rituals like opening the water taps at midnight can be seen, based on the belief in the abundance and prosperity that water brings.</li>
</ul>
<h3>4. Home and Street Decorations</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Decorating a Pine Tree:</b> This is the most distinct visual symbol of New Year&#8217;s, a celebration separate from Christmas in Turkey. Homes, shopping malls, and main streets are adorned with pine trees (New Year&#8217;s trees) decorated with <b>colorful lights, tinsel, and ornaments</b>. This is seen as a symbol of entering the new year with joy and hope.</li>
<li><b>Illuminations:</b> Especially in big cities, central streets like Nişantaşı (Istanbul) and Kızılay (Ankara) are transformed into festival-like areas with dazzling and spectacular light displays.</li>
</ul>
<h3>5. Gift Exchange (New Year&#8217;s Drawing)</h3>
